1
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:06,520
My bed, my bridal, all for misery. 

2
00:00:06,520 --> 00:00:07,840
And I cannot... 

3
00:00:09,080 --> 00:00:14,120
I cannot...save my child from death. 

4
00:00:14,120 --> 00:00:17,800
This is one of the most shocking stories ever written. 

5
00:00:17,800 --> 00:00:22,920
A mother, a princess, has lost her city and her husband in war. 

6
00:00:22,920 --> 00:00:27,280
Now, she has to face the news that she is to be sold into slavery 

7
00:00:27,280 --> 00:00:29,440
and her only son - killed. 

8
00:00:30,520 --> 00:00:34,440
This film version of an ancient Greek play called Trojan Women 

9
00:00:34,440 --> 00:00:36,320
has become a classic. 

10
00:00:36,320 --> 00:00:41,200
The first time I saw it, I was moved to tears, and it still moves me now. 

11
00:00:42,640 --> 00:00:47,280
It is a play about the most charged aspects of human life - 

12
00:00:47,280 --> 00:00:51,320
love, war, sacrifice, fear and death. 

13
00:00:51,320 --> 00:00:54,160
And although it is set amongst the gods, myths, 

14
00:00:54,160 --> 00:00:58,960
and peoples of ancient Greece, it is still utterly gripping today. 

15
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:01,800
It is one of the main reasons I study Classics. 

16
00:01:06,400 --> 00:01:10,000
An Athenian called Euripides wrote this play 

17
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,040
a little under two and a half thousand years ago. 

18
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:16,360
Back then, he was often ridiculed as an angry young man. 

19
00:01:16,360 --> 00:01:19,600
But, over time, his plays have come to symbolise 

20
00:01:19,600 --> 00:01:23,680
the incredible sophistication of ancient Greek civilisation. 

21
00:01:26,200 --> 00:01:31,320
That civilisation has influenced almost every aspect of our lives. 

22
00:01:31,320 --> 00:01:35,880
Not just drama, but politics, language, philosophy, 

23
00:01:35,880 --> 00:01:37,480
art and architecture. 

24
00:01:40,160 --> 00:01:43,360
To understand ourselves, it turns out, 

25
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:45,840
we need to understand the ancient Greeks. 

26
00:01:46,920 --> 00:01:50,120
And the best seat from which to do that, for my money, 

27
00:01:50,120 --> 00:01:51,440
is in the theatre. 

28
00:01:53,560 --> 00:01:58,320
This series is about how ancient drama changed our world. 

29
00:01:58,320 --> 00:01:59,920
It's the story of dramatists 

30
00:01:59,920 --> 00:02:02,760
like Aeschylus, Sophocles and Euripides, 

31
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:05,720
who revolutionised storytelling through plays 

32
00:02:05,720 --> 00:02:09,320
like Trojan Women, Antigone, Oedipus, and The Oresteia. 

33
00:02:10,640 --> 00:02:12,880
It's the story of how the Ancient Greeks 

34
00:02:12,880 --> 00:02:15,680
gave birth to tragedy and comedy. 

35
00:02:15,680 --> 00:02:19,960
And it's the story of how theatre spread throughout Greece and beyond, 

36
00:02:19,960 --> 00:02:22,240
becoming a benchmark of civilisation, 

37
00:02:22,240 --> 00:02:25,000
not just for Greeks, but for the world - 

38
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:26,720
then and now. 

39
00:02:28,160 --> 00:02:31,080
In this episode, I want to journey to Athens 

40
00:02:31,080 --> 00:02:34,400
to explore how drama first began. 

41
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:37,560
From the very start, it was about more than just entertainment - 

42
00:02:37,560 --> 00:02:42,040
it was a reaction to real events, it was a driving force in history, 

43
00:02:42,040 --> 00:02:45,680
and it was deeply connected to Athenian democracy. 

44
00:02:45,680 --> 00:02:49,880
In fact, the story of theatre, IS the story of Athens - 

45
00:02:49,880 --> 00:02:52,600
the cultural hub of ancient Greece 

46
00:02:52,600 --> 00:02:55,640
and the stage for one of the greatest shows on earth. 

47
00:03:15,840 --> 00:03:19,880
The story of drama as we know it begins in a particular place, 

48
00:03:19,880 --> 00:03:21,600
and a particular time - 

49
00:03:21,600 --> 00:03:24,960
Athens in the 6th century before Christ. 

50
00:03:24,960 --> 00:03:27,800
At that time, Greece was not a single country 

51
00:03:27,800 --> 00:03:31,200
but a mass of competing city-states, or "poleis" - 

52
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:34,040
the Greek term describing a body of citizens. 

53
00:03:35,040 --> 00:03:38,240
But in the late 6th century, the polis of Athens 

54
00:03:38,240 --> 00:03:40,160
pulled ahead of the others - 

55
00:03:40,160 --> 00:03:42,800
politically, economically and culturally. 

56
00:03:44,280 --> 00:03:46,560
In the last part of the 6th century BC, 

57
00:03:46,560 --> 00:03:50,680
Athens was the breeding ground for two extraordinary inventions. 

58
00:03:50,680 --> 00:03:52,240
The first was democracy. 

59
00:03:52,240 --> 00:03:55,560
Athens was ruled, not by kings or by cliques of aristocrats, 

60
00:03:55,560 --> 00:03:58,400
but by the votes of its own citizens. 

61
00:03:58,400 --> 00:04:00,640
But the second was theatre. 

62
00:04:00,640 --> 00:04:05,080
Athens invented an entirely new art form - drama. 

63
00:04:05,080 --> 00:04:08,440
And these two inventions were tightly intertwined 

64
00:04:08,440 --> 00:04:11,280
at the beating heart of Athenian society. 

65
00:04:11,280 --> 00:04:13,440
And both of them were the result 

66
00:04:13,440 --> 00:04:16,120
of an extraordinary cultural revolution. 

67
00:04:19,440 --> 00:04:22,240
At this time, the whole of ancient Greek culture 

68
00:04:22,240 --> 00:04:25,200
underwent a historic transformation. 

69
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:28,240
The revolution extended from architecture to literature, 

70
00:04:28,240 --> 00:04:30,800
from vase painting to philosophy. 

71
00:04:30,800 --> 00:04:33,440
You can see the impact of that revolution clearly 

72
00:04:33,440 --> 00:04:35,920
in how Greek sculpture developed. 

73
00:04:35,920 --> 00:04:39,080
In the middle 6th century it was rigid, stylised, 

74
00:04:39,080 --> 00:04:40,560
lacking movement and life. 

75
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:43,480
But then things began to change. 

76
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:46,000
By the 5th century, Greek artists began 

77
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:49,720
to produce some of the greatest life-like sculptures ever made. 

78
00:04:50,920 --> 00:04:53,880
It all amounted, not just to a new-looking world, 

79
00:04:53,880 --> 00:04:56,680
but to a whole new view of the world. 

80
00:04:56,680 --> 00:04:59,280
We call it the Classical World. 

81
00:04:59,280 --> 00:05:01,880
And in this ground-breaking epoch, 

82
00:05:01,880 --> 00:05:05,360
drama was perhaps the biggest innovation of them all. 

83
00:05:07,960 --> 00:05:12,320
Tales of love, death and war had always been passed on 

84
00:05:12,320 --> 00:05:16,120
by storytellers and epic poems like Homer's Iliad 

85
00:05:16,120 --> 00:05:20,080
and savage myths had been celebrated in choral dance and song. 

86
00:05:20,080 --> 00:05:25,560
BUT the Athenians added actors and invented the idea of performance. 

87
00:05:25,560 --> 00:05:29,680
These epic stories would now play out, not only in the mind, 

88
00:05:29,680 --> 00:05:32,400
but live on stage. 

89
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:35,560
This was more than innovation, this was a revolution. 

90
00:05:37,160 --> 00:05:39,440
Never before in the Greek tradition that we know of, 

91
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:41,280
in the Greek storytelling tradition, 

92
00:05:41,280 --> 00:05:44,760
were things enacted rather than narrated. 

93
00:05:44,760 --> 00:05:48,760
So, instead of having, "And then the king drew his sword and said..." 

94
00:05:48,760 --> 00:05:53,120
Instead, a person actually draws a sword and speaks. 

95
00:05:53,120 --> 00:05:55,720
I know we sort of say, "Well, children do that" 

96
00:05:55,720 --> 00:05:58,720
but to do it with serious storytelling, 

97
00:05:58,720 --> 00:06:01,800
with storytelling that actually delves into 

98
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:03,720
important roots in human behaviour, 

99
00:06:03,720 --> 00:06:08,360
that is a very new step and to have it done in front of you, 

100
00:06:08,360 --> 00:06:12,160
I think that must have been a very, very startling innovation. 

101
00:06:12,160 --> 00:06:14,200
- ACTOR:
- The son of Thyestes... 

102
00:06:14,200 --> 00:06:15,680
Ancient Greek drama looked 

103
00:06:15,680 --> 00:06:18,720
and sounded very different from drama as we know it today. 

104
00:06:18,720 --> 00:06:20,720
There were no more than three or four actors. 

105
00:06:20,720 --> 00:06:24,440
There was a chorus who interrupted the action with song and dance, 

106
00:06:24,440 --> 00:06:26,560
and all the performers wore masks. 

107
00:06:29,320 --> 00:06:33,280
When an actor began to enact rather than narrate, 

108
00:06:33,280 --> 00:06:35,840
there's a kind of dangerousness about that, 

109
00:06:35,840 --> 00:06:39,320
that the actor has to become a woman, 

110
00:06:39,320 --> 00:06:41,120
the actor has to become a slave, 

111
00:06:41,120 --> 00:06:43,200
the actor, perhaps even more dangerously, 

112
00:06:43,200 --> 00:06:46,720
has to become a god and it's almost as if the mask 

113
00:06:46,720 --> 00:06:50,400
is a kind of signal of the profession, 

114
00:06:50,400 --> 00:06:55,000
that protects the actor against the danger of doing these things. 

115
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:58,040
- ACTOR:
- Blood shoot of Aetrius... 

116
00:06:58,040 --> 00:07:02,960
'The chorus are costumed and masked in an identical' 

117
00:07:02,960 --> 00:07:06,720
or near identical way and they move and speak as a group. 

118
00:07:06,720 --> 00:07:08,720
The chorus is not a bunch of individuals - 

119
00:07:08,720 --> 00:07:10,920
for the Greeks, the chorus was a group. 

120
00:07:10,920 --> 00:07:14,200
In which, in a sense, they submerged their identity. 

121
00:07:14,200 --> 00:07:18,920
AND what the chorus does is, in its groupness, 

122
00:07:18,920 --> 00:07:22,960
it tries to make sense of what it's witnessing. 

123
00:07:22,960 --> 00:07:28,600
They're deeply emotionally involved, and the suffering becomes a song. 

124
00:07:28,600 --> 00:07:32,040
And the chorus, as a group, with its group response, 

125
00:07:32,040 --> 00:07:33,800
sings its choral lyrics. 

126
00:07:33,800 --> 00:07:37,120
- ACTOR:
- He plotted it? Single-handed? The people will stone him. 

127
00:07:37,120 --> 00:07:39,040
CHORUS: You don't stand a chance. 

128
00:07:42,360 --> 00:07:47,240
It seems to me, that the crucial thing is that it is simultaneously 

129
00:07:47,240 --> 00:07:49,840
a very strong emotional experience 

130
00:07:49,840 --> 00:07:52,040
and a very strong thought experience. 

131
00:07:57,960 --> 00:08:00,560
When the Greeks came to analyse their new art form, 

132
00:08:00,560 --> 00:08:03,360
they discerned three different types of play. 

133
00:08:03,360 --> 00:08:06,560
Two of which we still have with us today - tragedy and comedy. 

134
00:08:06,560 --> 00:08:09,760
But, in many ways, modern tragedy has actually changed 

135
00:08:09,760 --> 00:08:11,760
from how ancient tragedy worked. 

136
00:08:11,760 --> 00:08:15,040
For us, tragedy is a play with a sad ending, 

137
00:08:15,040 --> 00:08:18,240
but for the ancient Greeks, tragedy was a play 

138
00:08:18,240 --> 00:08:22,360
in which the events offered the audience a tough decision. 

139
00:08:22,360 --> 00:08:25,920
And because no real ancient tragedy ends conclusively - 

140
00:08:25,920 --> 00:08:28,640
siding with one course of action or another - 

141
00:08:28,640 --> 00:08:32,440
what it does is face the audience with a problem. 

142
00:08:32,440 --> 00:08:35,520
What would THEY do if they were in the same situation? 

143
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:40,520
Take one of the most famous plays ever written - 

144
00:08:40,520 --> 00:08:43,800
Oedipus The King by Sophocles. 

145
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:45,560
It tells the story of Oedipus, 

146
00:08:45,560 --> 00:08:49,800
a man who was destined to kill his father and marry his mother. 

147
00:08:49,800 --> 00:08:52,120
Although this outcome is predicted by an oracle, 

148
00:08:52,120 --> 00:08:54,840
Oedipus himself makes a series of free choices 

149
00:08:54,840 --> 00:08:56,640
that lead to its fulfilment - 

150
00:08:56,640 --> 00:09:00,640
choices that would have posed serious questions for the audience. 

151
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:04,360
The play ends with Oedipus blinding himself in despair. 

152
00:09:06,840 --> 00:09:10,000
The issues dealt with in tragedy were often so disturbing 

153
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:12,760
that the plays were nearly always set away from Athens, 

154
00:09:12,760 --> 00:09:16,960
in the land of myth and legend, or at very least a far away city. 

155
00:09:16,960 --> 00:09:18,840
And after a series of tragedies, 

156
00:09:18,840 --> 00:09:21,160
the Athenians were offered a satyr play. 

157
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:22,840
Now, we don't have this any more today 

158
00:09:22,840 --> 00:09:24,560
but effectively the satyrs 

159
00:09:24,560 --> 00:09:27,960
were the half-male, half-goat companions of the god of revelry, 

160
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:29,840
who would be allowed to run around the stage 

161
00:09:29,840 --> 00:09:32,800
doing lots of lewd and bawdy things as a bit of light relief. 

162
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:34,640
But what we do have today is comedy. 

163
00:09:34,640 --> 00:09:37,400
And ancient comedy, just like tragedy, 

164
00:09:37,400 --> 00:09:40,000
spoke directly to contemporary Athenians. 

165
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:46,880
Usually set in a topsy-turvy version of real life, 

166
00:09:46,880 --> 00:09:51,960
or in a realm of fantasy, they poked fun at contemporary Athens. 

167
00:09:51,960 --> 00:09:55,200
The Birds is a play that mocks the Athenian obsession 

168
00:09:55,200 --> 00:09:57,560
with litigation and politics. 

169
00:09:57,560 --> 00:09:59,320
It tells the story of two men 

170
00:09:59,320 --> 00:10:03,120
who are tired of a life of law courts and civic duties. 

171
00:10:03,120 --> 00:10:05,520
To escape, they turn themselves into birds 

172
00:10:05,520 --> 00:10:09,600
and create a bird city-in-the-sky called Cloud Cuckoo Land 

173
00:10:09,600 --> 00:10:14,520
where they reject all attempts to impose Athenian-style law and order. 

174
00:10:14,520 --> 00:10:18,480
Both comedy and tragedy sought to have a direct bearing 

175
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:20,240
on life in Athens. 

176
00:10:20,240 --> 00:10:23,840
And most fascinating of all, is how they seamlessly blended together 

177
00:10:23,840 --> 00:10:27,080
religion and myth with contemporary politics. 

178
00:10:27,080 --> 00:10:29,640
This means that a play like The Oresteia by Aeschylus 

179
00:10:29,640 --> 00:10:32,640
can start with a mythic tale from the Trojan wars 

180
00:10:32,640 --> 00:10:36,480
where Agamemnon is murdered by his wife and avenged by his son Orestes, 

181
00:10:36,480 --> 00:10:39,760
but can end in a courtroom, in democratic Athens, 

182
00:10:39,760 --> 00:10:43,200
with Orestes on trial for the murder of his mother. 

183
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:49,720
The Oresteia is one of the biggest hits in antiquity, 

184
00:10:49,720 --> 00:10:53,280
it's also one of the very few trilogies that we've got. 

185
00:10:53,280 --> 00:10:56,000
So what you have is three tragedies 

186
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:59,680
and, in this case, it's got a connected story. 

187
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:03,000
How does tragedy take this smorgasbord if you like, 

188
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:05,840
and make it into a story? 

189
00:11:05,840 --> 00:11:08,160
Well it's not the same problem for the ancient Greeks 

190
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:09,880
as it might be for us. 

191
00:11:09,880 --> 00:11:12,840
You know there's not this idea of anachronism. 

192
00:11:12,840 --> 00:11:17,480
Your mythical world, with the gods, with the Trojan war - 

193
00:11:17,480 --> 00:11:21,080
all of this that we've had in the first parts with the trilogy - 

194
00:11:21,080 --> 00:11:26,560
can then end in that third part with a law court in Athens, 

195
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:28,840
which would have been familiar, of course, 

196
00:11:28,840 --> 00:11:31,480
from 1st century contemporary Athens. 

197
00:11:31,480 --> 00:11:34,080
So you have this brilliant genre 

198
00:11:34,080 --> 00:11:38,000
where you can zoom from your present day into the past 

199
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:40,160
and bring your past into your present day. 

200
00:11:40,160 --> 00:11:41,760
And it's that relationship, 

201
00:11:41,760 --> 00:11:45,760
that tragedy uses to say things about its contemporary society. 

202
00:11:47,120 --> 00:11:50,440
To find out more about how drama and democratic Athens 

203
00:11:50,440 --> 00:11:52,760
became so intimately connected, 

204
00:11:52,760 --> 00:11:55,400
I want to look at how theatre first emerged. 

205
00:11:56,520 --> 00:11:58,200
Everything in ancient Greece 

206
00:11:58,200 --> 00:12:00,960
came under the auspices of a particular god, 

207
00:12:00,960 --> 00:12:04,360
and the god controlling theatre was called Dionysus. 

208
00:12:04,360 --> 00:12:06,920
He was also the god of wine and revelry 

209
00:12:06,920 --> 00:12:10,080
and many scholars think that theatre evolved directly 

210
00:12:10,080 --> 00:12:14,080
out of the choral songs performed in honour of Dionysus. 

211
00:12:14,080 --> 00:12:16,440
But there's also something else going on here. 

212
00:12:16,440 --> 00:12:18,760
Something that is suggested by the ruins 

213
00:12:18,760 --> 00:12:21,120
at a place called Thorikos, near Athens. 

214
00:12:22,160 --> 00:12:25,680
This region was once home to the ancient Athenian silver mines 

215
00:12:25,680 --> 00:12:27,320
but is also the site 

216
00:12:27,320 --> 00:12:30,720
of the oldest stone-built theatre in the Greek world. 

217
00:12:30,720 --> 00:12:34,400
We're in an industrial heartland of the ancient Athenian state, 

218
00:12:34,400 --> 00:12:36,480
with the ore washeries and the mineshafts 

219
00:12:36,480 --> 00:12:38,240
just beyond the theatre here. 

220
00:12:39,400 --> 00:12:42,400
The first phase of this theatre is late 6th century 

221
00:12:42,400 --> 00:12:44,200
and that puts it in the same time 

222
00:12:44,200 --> 00:12:47,160
as the invention of Athenian democracy itself. 

223
00:12:47,160 --> 00:12:49,160
Which throws up another question - 

224
00:12:49,160 --> 00:12:54,040
just what is the relationship between theatre and democracy? 

225
00:12:54,040 --> 00:12:57,040
And how did the two help each other into being? 

226
00:13:02,080 --> 00:13:05,840
It's a question that has been debated by scholars for centuries - 

227
00:13:05,840 --> 00:13:09,840
were theatre and democracy connected from the very start? 

228
00:13:09,840 --> 00:13:14,360
Now I actually buy into the story that tragic drama 

229
00:13:14,360 --> 00:13:17,000
IS a democratic invention. 

230
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:18,680
I have a particular take 

231
00:13:18,680 --> 00:13:22,920
because I am one of those who think that Athenian tragic drama 

232
00:13:22,920 --> 00:13:25,680
was deeply, strongly politicised. 

233
00:13:25,680 --> 00:13:29,240
Not just, it happened in a polis but it happened in a polis 

234
00:13:29,240 --> 00:13:33,800
of a particular sort and could not have happened before Athens 

235
00:13:33,800 --> 00:13:38,080
became a polis of that particular sort, a democratic one. 

236
00:13:38,080 --> 00:13:41,640
The theatrical side seems to coincide 

237
00:13:41,640 --> 00:13:45,160
fairly closely with the political identity. 

238
00:13:45,160 --> 00:13:47,280
Theatrical activities of some sort or another 

239
00:13:47,280 --> 00:13:50,080
were one of the ways in which they expressed the fact 

240
00:13:50,080 --> 00:13:51,840
that now they all belonged together, 

241
00:13:51,840 --> 00:13:54,800
this was the place to which they came and in which they acted. 

242
00:13:54,800 --> 00:13:56,200
It's about, you know, 

243
00:13:56,200 --> 00:13:59,600
the local community feeling itself to be a local community. 

244
00:14:01,240 --> 00:14:04,920
I'm on my way to visit one of the smaller Athenian communities 

245
00:14:04,920 --> 00:14:06,920
to try and find some more proof 

246
00:14:06,920 --> 00:14:10,160
about the connection between drama and politics. 

247
00:14:10,160 --> 00:14:13,240
I want to see what the archaeology itself has to say. 

248
00:14:14,320 --> 00:14:16,280
Now, neither for theatre nor for democracy, 

249
00:14:16,280 --> 00:14:18,320
was there any kind of immaculate conception. 

250
00:14:18,320 --> 00:14:21,440
Nor were either born into the fully-developed form 

251
00:14:21,440 --> 00:14:23,160
that we recognize them today. 

252
00:14:23,160 --> 00:14:26,200
Both developed, arm-in-arm, over time. 

253
00:14:26,200 --> 00:14:28,160
And all around us as we drive in Attica, 

254
00:14:28,160 --> 00:14:29,720
we can see the building blocks, 

255
00:14:29,720 --> 00:14:32,800
the basis of the Athenian democratic system. 

256
00:14:37,440 --> 00:14:40,200
People tend to think of Athenians as city dwellers, 

257
