325
00:18:29,480 --> 00:18:32,080
The procession then surged through the streets 

326
00:18:32,080 --> 00:18:34,320
along a route lined with tripods - 

327
00:18:34,320 --> 00:18:38,520
monuments put up by the proud sponsors of the winning plays. 

328
00:18:38,520 --> 00:18:40,160
Often politicians, 

329
00:18:40,160 --> 00:18:43,240
they spent fortunes funding dramatic productions, 

330
00:18:43,240 --> 00:18:46,600
and marked their victories with monuments like this one - 

331
00:18:46,600 --> 00:18:49,160
put up by a winner from the 4th century BC. 

332
00:18:51,480 --> 00:18:55,480
So, the drama festival was more than an opportunity for staging plays, 

333
00:18:55,480 --> 00:18:58,280
it was a chance for the leading figures of Athens 

334
00:18:58,280 --> 00:19:03,360
to stage their generosity, and their success to the whole city. 

335
00:19:03,360 --> 00:19:07,120
Finally, having wound its way right around the Acropolis, 

336
00:19:07,120 --> 00:19:11,480
the procession emerged noisily into the precinct of Dionysus. 

337
00:19:11,480 --> 00:19:15,480
By now, the participants were becoming a single entity. 

