350
00:19:55,400 --> 00:19:59,320
- It's a bit different to going to the theatre today, right?
- It is indeed. 

351
00:20:01,200 --> 00:20:04,560
All of this put the audience into a receptive state 

352
00:20:04,560 --> 00:20:07,360
for the drama competition that was to follow. 

353
00:20:07,360 --> 00:20:10,080
But first, as they took their seats in the theatre, 

354
00:20:10,080 --> 00:20:13,040
there was one more important set of rituals to come. 

355
00:20:14,840 --> 00:20:16,960
The audience were seated here, 

356
00:20:16,960 --> 00:20:20,640
perhaps in the same groupings as when they went to war. 

357
00:20:20,640 --> 00:20:22,880
The citizens of Athens who were acting on the stage, 

358
00:20:22,880 --> 00:20:26,600
were acting in the same groups as when they went to war. 

359
00:20:26,600 --> 00:20:29,400
And in the front seats of the theatre were the reserved seats 

360
00:20:29,400 --> 00:20:33,120
for various priests of the city, and for the important civic officials. 

361
00:20:34,280 --> 00:20:38,040
And then, before the plays began, there were a series of events. 

362
00:20:38,040 --> 00:20:41,600
First, a libation - an offering to the gods were poured 

363
00:20:41,600 --> 00:20:43,840
in the centre of the stage by the generals, 

364
00:20:43,840 --> 00:20:46,040
the military generals of the city. 

365
00:20:46,040 --> 00:20:49,400
Then, a parade of tribute, 

366
00:20:49,400 --> 00:20:52,760
of all the money paid by the cities and states of the Athenian empire 

367
00:20:52,760 --> 00:20:56,480
to Athens, was literally taken across the stage, 

368
00:20:56,480 --> 00:20:59,880
paraded in front of an audience that contained members 

369
00:20:59,880 --> 00:21:03,680
from those same city-states which had to pay all that money. 

