00:21:03,680 --> 00:21:06,760
Then a list of all those who had benefited the city in some way 

371
00:21:06,760 --> 00:21:08,280
was read out. 

372
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:12,840
And finally, onto the stage were brought the orphans, 

373
00:21:12,840 --> 00:21:16,800
those whose parents had died fighting for the city in battle 

374
00:21:16,800 --> 00:21:18,920
and whom the city would now 

375
00:21:18,920 --> 00:21:22,000
take on the expenses of bringing up and educating. 

376
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:26,520
They came on, dressed themselves in the armour of war 

377
00:21:26,520 --> 00:21:30,080
and took their seats, their special seats here in the theatre. 

378
00:21:30,080 --> 00:21:32,360
Only then could the plays begin. 

379
00:21:35,240 --> 00:21:38,080
From dawn until dusk, for five days, 

380
00:21:38,080 --> 00:21:40,840
the citizen audience watched three playwrights 

381
00:21:40,840 --> 00:21:44,880
each put on three tragedies as well as a farcical satyr play, 

382
00:21:44,880 --> 00:21:46,400
and some comedies. 

383
00:21:46,400 --> 00:21:49,600
At their heart were issues of justice and loyalty, 

384
00:21:49,600 --> 00:21:52,880
war and peace, vengeance and compassion, 

385
00:21:52,880 --> 00:21:56,040
which sent powerful messages to the citizen audience. 

386
00:21:59,200 --> 00:22:01,200
In the centuries of Athens' greatness, 

387
00:22:01,200 --> 00:22:04,920
over 1,000 plays were written for the Dionysia. 

388
00:22:04,920 --> 00:22:09,480
But today, just 32 of them survive in full. 

389
00:22:09,480 --> 00:22:11,640
And those 32 have survived, in part, 

390
00:22:11,640 --> 00:22:14,240
because they were considered to be the greatest. 

391
00:22:14,240 --> 00:22:17,160
And they were all written by just three people - 

392
00:22:17,160 --> 00:22:20,080
Aeschylus, Sophocles, Euripides - 

